<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Tips</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
1) Quick heal/repair - I hope by now everyone is using the favorites feature to load up at equipment terminals. There is a quick way to repair your armor and heal yourself if you have access to a terminal.<br>
<br>
I call it my quick repair favorite and you just need to have a different type of armor than the one you are wearing in this load out as well as a few med kits. Simply change to this armor (for me it's standard), heal once or more, and then change to your preferred load out. <br>
<br>
EG: I go up to a terminal and hit G,5,heal,G,1,heal,G,1 and I'm fully healed/repaired in about 3 seconds. Faster than a med terminal and handy at an AMS in the field.<br>
<br>
2) Finding squad mates/using the map - once you are in a squad, you don't need to ask where people are, simply use the map. Once in the map (M), hit G to get global view, and look for your squad mates numbers. Double click to zoom into the continent they are on et voila.<br>
<br>
3) Medium weapons - everyone should at least have this cert. The cycler is 10 times better than the default rifle. It has 4x zoom, holds 50 ammo at once and should be fired in bursts, not full auto (unless yer in the enemy's face). The punisher is versatile, good for close quarters (but not for me). The shotgun sucks imo, but it's there.<br>
<br>
4) AP ammo - I read a lot of people in beta saying AP ammo sucked and why bother. I'll tell you why: you can take on maxes and vehicles with this stuff and actually have a chance. If I can get behind a max in close quarters I can usually kill him np as long as I stay behind him (fairly easy in agile). Takes about 70-80 rounds. I've taken on a VS thresher solo, on a hill and beat him. Sniping VS maxes = fun! Scaring reavers also = fun! Regular ammo, you might as well give up.<br>
<br>
5) Getting around sanctuary - I think we all know this one now...and that I have to explain it to new people almost every night...but until everyone knows it, I'm gonna have to keep explaining it. At the corner of each HART building in each sanctuary village, are what I call bus stops. Mini warp gates that toggle you between each of the 3 WG villages. Simply walk thru, hack your map to see where you are, walk thru again if you need to.<br>
<br>
6) Getting around bases - This will come with time. Remember that only AMP stations and Tech facilities are UP, rest are down. AMP = outside and up in the dome, Tech = inside up by the air vehicle terminals.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.planetside-universe.com/staticfacil.php">www.planetside-universe.c...cfacil.php</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
7) Darklight vision - I think this is mandatory at level 6. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Binding - Every base has a &quot;matrixing panel&quot;. Find it and use it whenever you can. It means you can spawn at it even if you are not close to it...even on another continent. Especially useful for me at dropship centers. So guys with vehicle certs, bind at the base so you can get back to get vehicles easily.<br>
<br>
9) Know your team-mates - I'm finding this challenging atm, to know what everyone is certed in. Especially when it's so easy to change. Not like EQ/DAoC where you know what class people are. This will improve with time. I want to get some kind of spreadsheet going tho, or some chart to classify people. <br>
<br>
Also, know that some people know base layouts, etc better than you. So stick together. ie: I know where the CC is in every base now, so if you enter the base with me, follow me cuz I'll be hacking asap. It's always good to have people at my back when hacking the base. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Strategies</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
1) Quiet base - the more spawn points we have the better chances we have at not losing the base. Especially if we are working alone. Key steps to taking a quiet base: <br>
   a) Galaxy/sunderer drops off hacker/combat engineer at nearest tower then moves onto base<br>
   b) hacker/engineer secure tower, set up turrets/sensors<br>
   c) rest of squad hot drops on base, secures CC<br>
   d) AMS driver hacks vehicle term and sets up AMS near base right away. Don't even wait for the hack. 2 AMSs if possible.<br>
   e) engineer sets up turrets/sensors at back door of base, then front door and perimeter if possible<br>
   f) optional: Tank/jeep/sunderer/etc driver get vehicle/gunners to patrol if we have man power. Also useful to pick people up who are at other bases and get them back.<br>
<br>
<br>
2) AMS setup - a lot of people set these up in the CY (court yard) of a base. While handy, it is easily found. For the first AMS, I prefer it to be a good distance away and well hidden. If we have 2 or more, one in the CY is good. Also, know that the cloaking bubble is a complete sphere. It can be seen from the basement and thru walls. So if you park next to a facility wall, know that the enemy will be able to spot it on the other side or from below.<br>
<br>
3) Scouting ahead - the thing I hate most when flying a squad in a galaxy is getting to the target base only to find the enemy presence there extremely high and losing the galaxy and squad members in a matter of seconds. At least one mosquito/reaver would be ideal to scout ahead and report back.<br>
<br>
4) Non-stop dying bases - for those really hot hotspots, all plans go to hell. Typing = death. Checking map = death. Setting waypoints = suicide. But some things to try and do amongst the chaos:<br>
   a) get as many AMSs set up as possible<br>
   b) set up turrets/sensors asap<br>
   c) !!!<br>
   <br>
5) ANT runs - someday I'd like to have an ANT team. A galaxy pilot, ANT driver and rear gunner. At the first sign of ANT needage, either get existing galaxy, load up ANT at nearest base, and jet to the WG. OR, immediately recall and get the show on the road:<br>
   a) first, make sure you are at the right WG to get to your destination. If not, use the bus stop.<br>
   b) pilot gets galaxy and gets to WG immediately.<br>
   c) driver gets ANT to WG, parks behind galaxy, loads up NTUs<br>
   d) gunner hauls ass to WG and gets in REAR gun position<br>
   c) ANT loads on galaxy<br>
   e) Galaxy busts thru WG<br>
   <br>
With practice, leader should be able to call for ANT run, and the designated team be en route with full ANT within minutes.<br>
<br>
This is of course an ideal situation, with probably 2 squads. Which brings me to my next point:<br>
<br>
6) Recruiting - yes, this is a strategy. I need more people to boss around. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Just like our policy in DAoC and EQ, if you group with cool people, who aren't in an outfit, invite them to check us out (website). If they are eager to join right away, and you think they are a good fit, let us know in game (me, Zato, Bier have invite power...as far as I know)<br>
<br>
If you have RL friends that aren't playing yet, give them yer CDs with the 7 day trial if you haven't already done so.<br>
<br>
Before we had our outfit, I was in an outfit that was fairly large. Most nights we have 3 galaxies full and we're storming bases with ease. It rocked. Hopefully we can get there soonish.<br>
<br>
<br>
Ok that's my ideas for now. Feedback and other ideas welcomed. <br>
