<br>
First, I'm not usre if everyone has this or you need to be CR1 to do it, but since we want to get everyone to CR1 anyways...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Personal waypoint.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> You get this by right clicking on the map. It sets a blue waypoint that only you can see. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Uses:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
- for gal pilot (or anyone driving/flying) set to the warpgate you are heading to so the leader doesnt need to set it. ie: from sanc or if going to anothher continent.<br>
<br>
- when you find an enemy AMS, quickly set it so you can find it again and so you can either set a real way point if you are the squad leader or tell the squad leader where to set it and help the SL move his WP until it is on yours.<br>
<br>
- when driving a windy road to another WP, set it at each turn <br>
<br>
- when flying to a WP but you don't want to fly right over enemy base, set this point off to one side so you swing out and around the base, etc<br>
<br>
- your current target (tower/base)<br>
<br>
- when in reaver and someone dies to magrider, mark where they died and take that @#!$er out!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Squad waypoints:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
When you click on the &quot;Set waypoint&quot; menu, you cursor now has waypoints turned on. Whenever you click, even in global view (G), you will set a waypoint. When you click the menu &quot;Set waypoint&quot; again or turn the map off, it toggles it off. No need to click the menu each time.<br>
<br>
A quick way to clear waypoints is to set all 4 close together (but not in the exact same spot or it won't work), then click all 4 again to clear them. That way you don't need to look all over the map to find them to clear them.<br>
<br>
This will be useful when we have 2+ squads and (if) you are trying to coordinate WPs. You don't have to coordinate WPs. For more on that, see below.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Working with 2 or more squads:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I'm going to talk about this in the TeamSpeak thread but I'll mention it here as well. Once we start getting 10+ people on TS and we are in battle, we need to concentrate on less chatter and only use TS for tactical data. But still have fun <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
<br>
Ok so with 2 squads, setting waypoints and objectives, etc gets more difficult. When you need repairs but the repair guy is in another squad, it's hard to find each other. At least until platoons is implemented. <br>
<br>
So a couple of suggestions: <br>
<br>
Squad leaders should preface commands with &quot;Squad 1 go here&quot;, &quot;Squad 2 go there&quot;. Platoon leader (designated, does not have to be a SL) can also use this. <br>
<br>
Waypoints can be coordinated between leaders, either in tells or better in voice. Just say &quot;Set WP1 to be the NE Anguta tower, WP2 base&quot;. Both leaders would clear up their WPs (see above) and set those. Now both squads have same WPs.<br>
<br>
However sometimes this won't be possible because of chaos or different objectives, so SLs will have to say &quot;Squad 1 goto WP3&quot; and &quot;Squad 2 goto WP2&quot;, etc.<br>
<br>
We'll have to play around with this a bit and see what works and what doesn't.<br>
<br>
I have more to post on multi-squad objectives, but will post it later.<br>
